    <h1>DPT_ProjectileSurfaceImpact</h1>
    <div class="subtitle">Modular Surface Reaction &amp; VFX Cleanup Utility<br>
    <span style="font-size: 11pt; font-style: normal;">Provides robust, contextual material variations by analyzing the exact physics layers involved in the collision. This enables ammunition types to dynamically map dirt, stone, wood, or water elements to distinct visual effects, audio arrays, and physical vertex-mesh surface marks (cracks, molehills, or trenches).</span></div>

    <div style="background-color: #1e293b; padding: 15px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 30px; border: 1px solid #334155; line-height: 1.8;">
        <strong style="color: #38bdf8; display: block; margin-bottom: 8px;">Quick Navigation Reference:</strong>
        <a href="#core-properties" style="color: #a5f3fc; margin-right: 20px; text-decoration: none;">1. Core Properties</a>
        <a href="#layer-effects" style="color: #a5f3fc; margin-right: 20px; text-decoration: none;">2. Layer Specific Effects</a>
        <a href="#cleanup-utility" style="color: #a5f3fc; margin-right: 20px; text-decoration: none;">3. Surface Mark Cleanup Utility</a>
        <a href="#workflow" style="color: #a5f3fc; margin-right: 20px; text-decoration: none;">4. Setup &amp; Integration Workflow</a>
        <a href="#support" style="color: #a5f3fc; text-decoration: none;">5. Support</a>
    </div>

    <div class="note">
        <strong>The Dual-Layer Audio Paradigm: Core Projectile Sounds vs. Surface Sweeteners</strong><br><br>
        To preserve memory and streamline assembly configurations, impact audio is divided into two operational segments:
        <br><br>
        <strong>1. The Projectile Audio Slot (Base Class):</strong> Located on the core projectile prefabs (Boulder, Cannonball, Ballista Bolt). This pool represents the universal kinetic energy, mass, and weight of the projectile itself (e.g., a heavy sub-bass thud or metallic displacement crack). This profile remains constant regardless of what object is hit because the mass of the projectile does not change.<br>
        <strong>2. The Surface Impact Audio Slot (This Module):</strong> Handled contextually by the <code>DPT_ProjectileSurfaceImpact</code> companion component. This represents the high-frequency debris layer or environmental reaction (e.g., splintering wood fibers, shattering rock shards, or loose dirt explosions) mapped exclusively to specific target physics layers.
    </div>

    <h2 id="core-properties">1. Core Properties</h2>
    
    <h3>Fallback Effects &amp; General Configuration</h3>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th style="width: 30%;">Property</th>
                <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Default Break VFX Prefab</strong></td>
                <td>The base fallback visual effect instantiated at the point of impact if the targeted physics layer does not match an entry in the specific layer effects list.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Default Impact Audio Clips</strong></td>
                <td>The fallback pool of high-frequency surface impact clips used if the hit physics layer does not match any custom layer configurations.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Pitch Variance</strong></td>
                <td>Controls the randomized frequency shift added or subtracted from the surface impact sounds to prevent audio repetition (Default: ±0.15).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Velocity Threshold</strong></td>
                <td>The minimum collision speed (m/s) required to trigger the specialized surface impact logic and visual effects. Low-speed grazes are ignored (Default: 2 m/s).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Horizontal Dot Threshold</strong></td>
                <td>Defines the slope cutoff for Horizontal vs Vertical surfaces used by the layer orientation filters. A value of <code>0.707</code> represents exactly a 45-degree angle.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Ground Check Radius</strong></td>
                <td>The radius of the physics SphereCast used to catch the ground. Prevents visual gaps in the rolling trench trail if a heavy boulder slightly bounces off uneven terrain (Default: 0.5).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Ground Check Distance</strong></td>
                <td>The downward travel distance the SphereCast evaluates to confirm continuous ground contact during a roll (Default: 0.6).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Min Roll Distance To Trench</strong></td>
                <td>Minimum continuous distance the projectile must roll on the ground before it begins carving a trench. Helps prevent trenches from spawning during erratic skipping.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Max Rolling Velocity</strong></td>
                <td>Maximum speed at which continuous rolling trenches will spawn, preventing gappy trenches during high-speed bouncing.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Impact VFX Settings</h3>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th style="width: 30%;">Property</th>
                <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Scale VFX With Speed</strong></td>
                <td>Dynamically scales the spawned particles based on the kinetic impact speed.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>VFX Scale Multiplier</strong></td>
                <td>Base scale modifier applied to the instantiated VFX.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Max Scale Velocity</strong></td>
                <td>The velocity at which the VFX reaches its maximum scale. Slower impacts will spawn smaller particle bursts.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Min Scale Multiplier</strong></td>
                <td>The baseline scale multiplier applied to the VFX even at very low collision speeds.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Align VFX With Velocity</strong></td>
                <td>Rotates the particle system to align with the projectile's velocity (flattened against the hit surface).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Fire VFX Backwards</strong></td>
                <td>Reverses the velocity alignment so dust and debris spray opposite to the travel direction.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2 id="layer-effects">2. Layer Specific Effects</h2>
    <p>An extensible array linking dynamic game layers directly to contextual cosmetic feedback modules.</p>

    <h3>Target Identification</h3>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th style="width: 30%;">Property</th>
                <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>LayerMask</strong></td>
                <td>The specific physics layer this effect applies to.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Orientation Filter</strong></td>
                <td>Filters this effect by surface angle (Any, Horizontal Only, Vertical Only). For optimal performance and control, it is highly recommended to use Layer Masks, but this filter allows surface effects to function out-of-the-box in demo scenes without configuring project layers.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Surface Audio Clips</strong></td>
                <td>The precise audio pool assigned to simulate structural degradation for that material type.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
<h3>Reaction Overrides</h3>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th style="width: 30%;">Property</th>
                <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Behavior Override</strong></td>
                <td>Overrides the base projectile's physical reaction when hitting this specific layer[cite: 6]. Options include <code>None</code> (default projectile settings), <code>ForceShatter</code>, <code>ForcePenetrate</code>, <code>ForceStop</code>, <code>ForceEmbed</code>, and <code>PreventEmbed</code>[cite: 6].</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Override Velocity Retention</strong></td>
                <td>Only used if <strong>Force Penetrate</strong> is selected[cite: 6]. Overrides the projectile's default velocity retention multiplier (0.0 to 1.0)[cite: 6].</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Override Embed Depth</strong></td>
                <td>Only used if <strong>Force Embed</strong> is selected. Overrides how deep the projectile sinks into this specific layer.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
<h3>Surface Audio</h3>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th style="width: 30%;">Property</th>
                <th>Description</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Surface Audio Clips</strong></td>
                <td>The precise audio pool assigned to simulate structural degradation for that material type.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Layer Pitch Variance</strong></td>
                <td>Random pitch variance applied specifically to this layer's impact sounds (± this value). Overrides the global pitch variance.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Layer Volume Variance</strong></td>
                <td>Random volume variance applied specifically to this layer's impact sounds (± this value).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td><strong>Layer Volume Multiplier</strong></td>
